"# Chapter 8 — Propositions as Types, Worked

Where we walk through five worked examples of the Curry-Howard
correspondence — theorem, type, term — in enough detail that the
correspondence stops being an abstraction and becomes a habit.

Chapter 7 laid out the correspondence. This chapter picks five theorems
of intuitionistic logic and writes their corresponding programs, one
by one, watching how the proof structure and the code structure line
up move for move. By the end, the two-way translation should feel
mechanical.

## Example 1: The identity theorem

The theorem: `P → P`. *Anything implies itself.*

The proof, in natural deduction:

    Assume P.
    Discharge: therefore P → P.

The type: `P → P`. The program:

```scheme
(define (id x) x)
;; type:  P → P  for any P
```

The Scheme function `id` is exactly the proof. Assume `x : P`; return
it as a witness of P; discharge the assumption to get a function of
type `P → P`. Read the code as a proof: given a proof of P (namely x),
return a proof of P (namely x). The proof is that boring.

That is the correspondence at its simplest. The identity function is
the identity theorem.

## Example 2: Hypothetical syllogism

The theorem: `(P → Q) → (Q → R) → P → R`. *Implication is transitive.*

Natural deduction proof:

    Assume f : P → Q.
    Assume g : Q → R.
    Assume x : P.
    From f and x, by modus ponens: (f x) : Q.
    From g and (f x), by modus ponens: (g (f x)) : R.
    Discharge x: (P → R).
    Discharge g: (Q → R) → (P → R).
    Discharge f: (P → Q) → (Q → R) → (P → R).

The program:

```scheme
(define (compose f g) (lambda (x) (g (f x))))
;; type:  (P → Q) → (Q → R) → P → R
```

Function composition *is* the proof of hypothetical syllogism. Every
time you compose two functions, you are silently proving a theorem of
implicational logic. This is the reason function composition feels
mathematically inevitable — it is inevitable in exactly the same way
transitivity is inevitable in ordering.

## Example 3: Commutativity of conjunction

The theorem: `P ∧ Q → Q ∧ P`. *And is commutative.*

Natural deduction proof:

    Assume p : P ∧ Q.
    Apply conj-elim-l: (fst p) : P.
    Apply conj-elim-r: (snd p) : Q.
    Apply conj-intro: (pair (snd p) (fst p)) : Q ∧ P.
    Discharge p: (P ∧ Q) → (Q ∧ P).

The program:

```scheme
(define (swap p)
  (cons (cdr p) (car p)))
;; type:  (P × Q) → (Q × P)
```

Reordering the elements of a pair is a proof of the commutativity of
conjunction. When you write `swap` in a data-processing pipeline you
are quietly using this theorem. When you cannot easily *avoid* using
`swap`, you can conclude that your data type has a genuine order that
matters — the type is not really a symmetric conjunction.

## Example 4: Distribution of conjunction over disjunction

The theorem: `P ∧ (Q ∨ R) → (P ∧ Q) ∨ (P ∧ R)`. *And distributes over or.*

This is where the correspondence gets interesting because there is a
*case analysis*.

Natural deduction proof:

    Assume p : P ∧ (Q ∨ R).
    From p by conj-elim-l: (fst p) : P.
    From p by conj-elim-r: (snd p) : Q ∨ R.
    Case-analyse (snd p):
      Case (inl q):  q : Q; so (pair (fst p) q) : P ∧ Q;
                     so (inl (pair (fst p) q)) : (P ∧ Q) ∨ (P ∧ R).
      Case (inr r):  r : R; so (pair (fst p) r) : P ∧ R;
                     so (inr (pair (fst p) r)) : (P ∧ Q) ∨ (P ∧ R).
    Discharge p.

The program:

```scheme
(define (distribute p)
  (let ((a  (car p))
        (qr (cdr p)))
    (cond
      ((eq? (car qr) 'inl)
       (cons 'inl (cons a (cdr qr))))
      ((eq? (car qr) 'inr)
       (cons 'inr (cons a (cdr qr)))))))
;; type: P × (Q + R)  →  (P × Q) + (P × R)
```

Case-analysis in the proof becomes a `cond` in the program. Every branch
of the `cond` produces a value on one side of the sum. The tags 'inl
and 'inr in our representation mark which side of the disjunction we
are in. The program is a proof by cases; the code just makes the
cases explicit.

## Example 5: De Morgan (one direction)

The theorem: `¬P ∧ ¬Q → ¬(P ∨ Q)`. *If both are false, then their
disjunction is false.*

Reminder: `¬X` corresponds to `X → Empty`.

Natural deduction proof:

    Assume p : ¬P ∧ ¬Q.
    Assume d : P ∨ Q. (We aim to derive ⊥ from these two.)
    Case-analyse d:
      Case (inl x): x : P. Combine with (fst p) : ¬P — that is
                    (fst p) : P → Empty. Apply to x: ((fst p) x) : Empty.
      Case (inr y): y : Q. Combine with (snd p) : ¬Q. Apply to y:
                    ((snd p) y) : Empty.
    Discharge d: (P ∨ Q) → Empty, i.e., ¬(P ∨ Q).
    Discharge p: (¬P ∧ ¬Q) → ¬(P ∨ Q).

The program:

```scheme
(define (demorgan-fwd p)
  (lambda (d)
    (cond
      ((eq? (car d) 'inl) ((car p) (cdr d)))     ; (fst p) applied to x : P
      ((eq? (car d) 'inr) ((cdr p) (cdr d))))))  ; (snd p) applied to y : Q
;; type:  (¬P × ¬Q) → ¬(P ∨ Q)
;;     = (P → Empty) × (Q → Empty) → (P + Q) → Empty
```

The pattern is the same as before. Case-analysis becomes `cond`, and
each case invokes the appropriate refutation function. The program
never actually produces anything in Empty (it cannot, Empty has no
values); it demonstrates the emptiness by showing that whichever case
we are in, we could produce something in Empty if only the premise were
truthful.

Note the other direction of De Morgan — `¬(P ∨ Q) → ¬P ∧ ¬Q` — is also
constructively valid. But the *other* De Morgan pair — going between
`¬(P ∧ Q)` and `¬P ∨ ¬Q` — only holds *one way* constructively:
`¬P ∨ ¬Q → ¬(P ∧ Q)` is fine, but `¬(P ∧ Q) → ¬P ∨ ¬Q` is not. It
requires the excluded middle. Try to write the program for the second
direction and you will get stuck exactly where the classical proof uses
LEM.

## The pattern: proof structure = code structure

Every one of these five examples had the same shape:

- Assumptions become function arguments (`λx. ...`).
- Conjunction becomes pair (`cons`, `car`, `cdr`).
- Disjunction becomes tagged sum with case-analysis (`cond` on the tag).
- Application of an implication becomes function application.
- Introduction of an implication becomes function definition.

The proof is *literally the same object* as the program. Not analogous,
not similar — the same object. The two representations differ only in
whether you write `(cons a b)` or `(pair-intro a b)`, `λx.body` or
`(assume x; body; discharge x)`. They are notational variants.

## The Kolmogorov interpretation

There is an older name for this: the *Brouwer-Heyting-Kolmogorov*
interpretation, or *BHK*. It predates Curry-Howard by decades and gives
the reading directly.

- A proof of `A ∧ B` is a pair (proof of A, proof of B).
- A proof of `A ∨ B` is a tagged proof: either of A or of B, with the
  tag showing which.
- A proof of `A → B` is a construction that turns any proof of A into
  a proof of B.
- A proof of `∀x. P(x)` is a construction that, given any x in the
  domain, produces a proof of P(x).
- A proof of `∃x. P(x)` is a pair (witness x, proof of P(x)).
- A proof of `⊥` does not exist.
- A proof of `¬A` is a construction that, given any proof of A, produces
  a proof of ⊥.

Read that list and compare it to the type constructors in a functional
language. They line up perfectly. Kolmogorov's interpretation *is*
Curry-Howard, expressed as a philosophy of proof rather than as a
correspondence with types. Which came first depends on whom you ask;
in any case, the ideas landed on top of one another and lasted.

## Where the correspondence extends

We have seen Curry-Howard for intuitionistic propositional logic and
simply-typed lambda calculus. There are richer correspondences for
richer systems.

- **First-order intuitionistic logic** ↔ **dependent type theory
  (Martin-Löf)**. Quantifiers become dependent products (Π) and
  dependent sums (Σ). This is the basis of Agda and Idris.
- **Second-order intuitionistic logic** ↔ **System F**. Quantifiers over
  propositions become quantifiers over types.
- **Classical propositional logic** ↔ **lambda calculus with control
  operators** (call/cc). Griffin's 1990 correspondence.
- **Modal S4** ↔ **staged computation / metaprogramming**. Davies-
  Pfenning 1996.
- **Linear logic** ↔ **linear type systems** (Wadler 1990, Bierman 1994).
  Girard's linear logic corresponds to type systems where every value is
  used exactly once — the foundation of ownership types in Rust, of
  session types in concurrent languages.
- **Modal logic (temporal, epistemic)** ↔ **effect types / capability
  types**. Modern research (2010s+) has developed correspondences with
  many industrial type systems.

The pattern that emerges: nearly every interesting logic has a
computational correspondent. Chapter 9 will explore modal logic
directly. Chapter 11 will explore linear logic. The idea that types
are propositions is a wedge that opens many doors.

## Where the correspondence does not extend (obviously)

Some logics resist. Second-order *classical* logic corresponds to
something, but that something is not as clean. Modal logic with
non-normal modalities can be hard to find a type-theoretic reading
for. Substructural logics (relevance, affine) each have their own
correspondence but the details are delicate.

The trend: give a logic a Kripke semantics (worlds and accessibility
relations) and there is *usually* a computational correspondence to
some form of *staged* or *distributed* or *effectful* computation.

## Homotopy type theory: types are spaces

The most surprising modern extension: *homotopy type theory* (HoTT), a
research programme launched around 2010 and consolidated in the
Univalent Foundations project (Voevodsky et al., 2013). HoTT reads
types not just as propositions but as *homotopy types* — as spaces up
to continuous deformation. Two types are *equivalent* if they are
homotopy-equivalent as spaces. Every proof is a path in the space.

This has led to a new foundation for mathematics with *univalence* as
an axiom (isomorphic types are equal) and to fully mechanised proofs of
theorems in synthetic homotopy theory. It is beautiful and unfinished
research. You do not need it for programming, but you should know it
exists as the current frontier of Curry-Howard.

## Extracting a program from a proof

One of the industrial uses of the correspondence: prove a theorem in a
proof assistant, then extract the proof as executable code.

Consider the theorem: *for every list, there exists a sorted permutation
of that list.* In Coq/Agda this is:

    ∀ (l : List A) . ∃ (m : List A) . (Sorted m ∧ Permutation l m)

A proof of this theorem, mechanically extracted to Scheme, would be a
function `sort : List A → List A` with a *guarantee* that the output is
a sorted permutation of the input.

The extraction machinery: given a proof term, walk through it and drop
the parts of the term that only carry proof information (not
computational information). What remains is the computational content —
the algorithm. Coq has an `Extraction` tactic that does this and can
produce OCaml, Haskell, or Scheme code. The extracted code is *provably
correct* — it satisfies the theorem it was extracted from.

Real deployed systems built this way exist. CompCert extracts to OCaml.
Fiat Cryptography extracts to C. Each is correct-by-construction: the
algorithm's correctness was proved as a theorem, and the executable
code is the proof term.

## Try this

Take the theorem `((P → Q) → P) → P` (Peirce's law). This is *classically*
valid but not *constructively* valid. Try to write a Scheme function of
its type. You will get stuck. The place you get stuck is exactly where
classical proof used excluded middle. Notice the stuck point; it is a
diagnostic of what non-constructive reasoning would need.

Take the theorem `P → ¬¬P`. Write the program. It should type-check as
`P → (P → Empty) → Empty`. The trick: given a proof of P and a proof of
¬P, apply the second to the first. Simple. Notice you *cannot* prove
the reverse `¬¬P → P` in the same style; that direction requires
excluded middle.

Prove associativity of pairing: `(A × B) × C → A × (B × C)`. Then
prove its reverse. Then compose them. What do you get? A pair of
functions that witnesses the *isomorphism* of the two associations of
conjunction. Isomorphism at the type level is equivalence at the
proposition level.

## Closing

Five worked examples. Every proof becomes a program by direct
translation. Every program of a certain type is a proof of the
corresponding theorem.

This is not merely elegant. It has industrial consequences: it lets
proof assistants extract executable programs from proofs. It has
foundational consequences: it lets us build constructive mathematics
on programming. It has pedagogical consequences: it lets us teach
proof theory by teaching typed programming, and vice versa.

Chapters 9-12 explore where the correspondence goes: modal logic
becomes staged programming, temporal logic becomes protocol
verification, linear logic becomes resource-typed programming, and
category theory becomes a language of composition that unifies all
of these under a single algebraic frame.
"
